<h3>The Zillow Problem</h3>
<p>Independent agents cannot beat Zillow for "homes for sale in [city]." Zillow has a domain authority above 90 and millions of indexed pages. Trying to rank for broad, national terms is a losing strategy.</p>
<p>The winning strategy targets keywords Zillow ignores. Hyperlocal neighborhood guides. Specific buyer questions. Long-tail searches with high purchase intent. These are the terms where an independent agent with local expertise can outrank a national portal.</p>
<h2>Chapter 2: Keyword Research for Real Estate</h2>
<p>Most real estate agents target the wrong keywords. They chase "homes for sale" or "real estate agent" and wonder why they never rank. Those terms have astronomical competition and low conversion rates for individual agents.</p>
<p>The right approach targets <a href="/glossary/long-tail-keywords/">long-tail keywords</a> with local modifiers. These have less competition, higher intent, and better conversion rates.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="4 real estate keyword categories organized by search intent and difficulty" src="/images/blog/real-estate-keyword-categories.webp" /></p>
<h3>Four Keyword Categories for Real Estate</h3>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Category</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Intent</th>
<th>Difficulty</th>
</tr>
